column168: While screening using Xray, there was battery pack that I was concerned about lead me to open the package. Battery was ok but other undeclared hazmats were found.

ON 1/31/2018 A FUEL TRANSPORT TRUCK THIRD-PARTY CARRIER WAS LOADING AT THE ST. PAUL PARK REFINING CO. TRUCK LOADING RACK. THE THIRD PARTY CARRIER TRUCK HAS A SUDDEN LOSS OF CONTAINMENT FROM THE TOP OF THE TRAILER FOLLOWED BY AN EXPLOSION AND FIRE. THE THIRD PARTY DRIVER AND OTHER DRIVERS IN THE AREA EVACUATED THE LOADING RACK AREA AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES. THE SAFETY SYSTEMS WERE ACTIVATED AND WATER/FOAM DELUGE SYSTEMS OPERATED AS DESIGNED. THE ST. PAUL PARK REFINERY EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM SECURED THE AREA AND WERE ABLE TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE AND CLEAR THE INCIDENT WITHIN 2 HOURS.  FOLLOWING THE EMERGENCY INCIDENT, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE VAPOR VALVE ON THE CARGO TANK TRAILER OF THE THIRD PARTY CARRIER DID NOT OPERATE PROPERLY CAUSING VAPORS TO REMAIN IN THE TANK AND AN UNKNOWN IGNITION SOURCE OCCURRED CAUSING AN EXPLOSION AND FIRE.
column169: FOLLOWING A VERY DETAILED INVESTIGATION ST. PAUL PARK REFINING CO. HAS CORRECTIVE ACTIONS RECOMMENDED.  1. REQUIRE ALL THIRD PARTY CARRIERS THAT LOAD AT THE SPPR TERMINAL TO CERTIFY THAT EACH TRAILER AND EQUIPMENT MEEET THE MANUFACTURES TESTING AND MAINTENANCE RECOMMENDATIONS/REQUIREMENTS.  2. CONDUCT A REVIEW OF TERMINAL LOADING PROCEDURES/PROCESSES. 3. ENSURE ALL DRIVERS INTERNAL AND THIRD PARTY ARE PROPERLY TRAINED.

column168: 8 JAN 2018 – FIBU1251900 WAS LOADED AT OAK POINT “(13:56) – DEPARTED OAK POINT, CBSL WAS THE CARRIER “(15:45) – OMI RECEIVED CALL FROM PORTS AMERICA, ISO TANK LEAKING  “(16:15) – OMI ARRIVES AT PORT AND FINDS ISO ON SPILL CATCHER WITH SLOW DRIP COMING FROM CAP OF BOTTOM VALVE “(16:25) – OMI REMOVES CAP FROM VALVE AND 1 TBL SPOON OF PRODUCT RAN OUT “(16:33) – NOFD ARRIVES AND DEPARTS ONCE DETAILS OF EVENTS WERE EXPLAINED “(16:35) – CHEMTREC NOTIFIED “(16:45) – OMI BEGAN TROUBLE SHOOTING VALVE WHICH RESULTED IN THE CAPTURE OF APPROX ¼ CUP OF PRODUCT “(16:50) – OMI SPEAKS WITH LASP HAZMAT ABOUT INCIDENT DETAILS “(17:00) – INNER AND OUTER VALVES CONFIRMED TO BE WORKING CONDITION “(17:20) – NO LEAKS FOUND SO CAP WAS SECURELY SECURED. “(17:30) – OMI DEPARTED  THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE THE RESULT OF RESIDUAL PRODUCT REMAINING IN BETWEEN THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL VALVE. THE CAP WAS INSTALLED AND WAS NOT LOOSE BUT ALSO NOT COMPLETELY CLOSED AND COMPRESSING THE GASKET.
column169: LOOK BACK NEES TO BE PERFORMED TO DETERMINE THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE CAP NOT BEING PROPERLY INSTALLED.  THE PERSON RESPONSIBLE FOR THE CLOSURE AND THEIR SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. THIS WAS A TALKING POINT DURING PRODUCTION PLANNING MEETINGS TO HIGHLIGHT THE IMPORTANCE OF PROPERLY PREPARING CONTAINERS FOR SHIPMENT.

column168: While loading an outbound trailer the material handler attempted to enter the trailer with a double stacked pallet of drums. Upon contacting the dock plate the forklift rocked significantly causing the upper pallet to fail dropping one drum to the trailer floor. Upon striking the floor the cover on the drum became dislodged spilling its contents onto the trailer floor and into the pit dock. The material handler immediately closed the safety valve on the pit dock drain preventing the material from entering the storm drain. A third party vendor was contracted to mitigate the release. All related clean-up material was collected and disposed of properly.
column169: The material handler was retrained in forklift operations. Pallets will be loaded one at a time going forward rather than double stacking while moving onto the trailer.

column168: On 01/03/2018, at 1131, personnel in the CSXT Selkirk yard discovered NATX37241, a loaded tank car of Alcohols NOS, leaking from bottom outlet flange area. The car was isolated and Illinois Corn Processing LLC, NYS DEC and NRC were notified.  (CHEMTREC 2018-01-03-00094. HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the tank car was leaking from the bottom outlet flange area. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Doug Lathers 309-478-4442. Contractor personnel transferred the car product and decontaminated the car. The leak was secured and the car was placed on hold. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1.

column168: Intermodal container TRHU 393138 was reported leaking liquid in the Pearland Texas railyard on 1/3/2018. The BNSF Responder transloaded the product from the damaged tote into a good tote to prevent any further release.

column168: On 01/5/18 at 0437 hours CSX Mechanical Personnel in the CSXT Boyles Yard discovered UTLX11353, a loaded tank car of sulfuric acid had completely split in half during switching activities resulting in complete loss of all product. The area was isolated and the shipper Gus Navar with Mosaic (904-571-2953) was notified.  Hepaco, Marion Environmental, Environmental Management Services, Arcadis, and United States Environmental Services, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and discovered that approximately 13000 gallons of product had been released and the car in two separate pieces. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper contact Gus Navar with Mosaic (904-571-2953).         Tarrant, AL – 01/05/18 – UTLX11353– Sulfuric Acid

column168: On 1/9/18 at approximately 1:50 pm IMTT was in the process of loading an Ethyl Acrylate truck at the truck rack location. After approximately 1,964 gallons was loaded on the truck two IMTT Operators noticed that the flange behind the external valve was dripping. One of the Operators moved a catch pan under the drip and approximately 1/2 pint dripped into the pan. The loading operation was immediately shut down and the internal valve closed.  The two IMTT Operators blew the loading hose back to the tank from which the truck was being loaded.  Once the volume in the tanker truck was removed the truck was sent back to the transporter's location.
column169: IMTT contacted the customer of the product being loaded to inform them of the incident.  The customer of the product will work with the transporter to address any claims for lost product or delay in service.  The transporter will also address any necessary repairs to its trucks and associated equipment.

column168: A Veolia employee was using a drum cart to move a drum of paint related material product on the truck and loading dock at the Veolia 10-day intransit facility located in York, Pennsylvania.  The drum cart was not property placed under the steel drum causing the metal folk to puncture the bottom of the drum. A small pinhole leak caused by the metal folk of the drum cart resulted in the release of approximately 2 gallons of liquid to the sealed concrete dock floor area.  The drum was placed on its side and over packed into a savage drum.  All material was remediated and cleaned up with absorbents. All cleanup material was placed into the overpack DOT rated salvage drum.
column169: The Veolia employees were retrained on the proper use of drum carts and drum moving equipment.  They were also trained to inspect equipment before each use to ensure no defects are identified.

column168: At 1030 hrs. the local FRA Hazmat Inspector, while doing a routine inspection in the WLE Brewster yard, found that the Vapor Valve on tank car CTCX 780269 was leaking vapor.  The Inspector, Anthony Schneider called myself John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE, to come out and investigate.  When I arrived, I found that the valve handle on the Vapor Valve was loose.  The Valve plug was tight but I was able to get about another 3/4 turn out of the plug.  The shipper did install thread tape on the plug threads but the plug just wasn't tightened enough.  I closed the valve handle and the leak stopped and then I finished tightening the plug.  I then released the car for service.  I called Gibson Gas Company Emergency Number and Spoke with a Brian Cava about the problem.  He said he would talk to his folks about this problem.
column169: Better car securement procedures need to be followed.

column168: 0650 PTRA Trainmaster report product sloshing from manway on DOWX 74168 in the North Yard. Slick Response was notified at 0700 to respond to a leak on a Butyl Acrylate car located at the North Yard. Upon arriving on location, Slick personnel met with the yard master to gain access to the car. After placing the flags, and lockout onto track 47, personnel accessed the top of the car, where they found an eight-bolt many with all but two loose, less than tool tight. Slick found that bolts number 5 and 6 had approx. ¼” gap between the lid and the dome. They also found that numbers 1-2-3-4 were extremely loose, could be tightened by hand. After removing all the bolts. Slick personnel then opened the dome lid to check the gasket where they found the pressed seal had a tear. After removing the pressed gasket, Slick personnel placed a new gasket around the manway collar, then tightened the bolts down tool tight. Slick Response then washed/wiped down the residue product on the tank car exterior. Upon completion, Slick personnel contacted the PTRA to inform them what was found then informed the yardmaster that the flags and locks have been removed.
column169: Per Doug James, Transportation Safety & Security, The Dow Chemical Company, this car was loaded and secured by a 3rd Party company SGS at the DOW Rohm and Haas Deer Park, TX site.  Their contact info for compliance manager is Glenn Gillaspia, SGS Company, Regulatory Compliance Manager, 713-924-8051, Glenn.Gillaspia@sgs.com.

column168: A vacuum tanker, operated by a Clean Harbors Environmental driver, was loaded by facility personnel at the Huntsman Petrochemical facility. After the tanker was loaded, the driver moved the unit to the onsite scale to weigh the load prior to exiting the facility. It was during this movement that a small amount of the material was released from the dome hatch on the unit, caught in the overflow tray and subsequently released to the asphalt on Huntsman’s facility. Facility personnel, in proper personal protective equipment successfully remediated all impacted areas; asphalt only, no water ways, storm drains or soil were impacted. Through the investigation it was determined that the driver failed to check the securement of the dome hatch after facility personnel loaded the trailer, thus causing a release onsite. A courtesy report was made to Emily Bourg of the Texas Commission on Environmental Quality, who elected to not input the release into the states spill data base as it was below the reportable quantity, therefore no report number was generated. The tanker was thoroughly secured and made its way to its final disposal destination without further incident.
column169: The driver was retrained on proper load securement specific to  vacuum tanker operations and issued disciplinary action. Communication between the facility and Clean Harbors personnel relating to vacuum tanker loading and load securement was documented and used in a safety meeting for both parties.

IT WAS DETERMINED THAT IT BECAME LOOSE DURING TRANSPORTATION. THE SPILL AREA WAS CLEANED UP. THE DRUM OVER-PACKED AND WAS SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.

column168: At approximately 1435,the PTRA Pasadena Yardmaster received a call reporting a tank car leaking that was sitting on the Port Main in CTC. All rail traffic was stopped until assessment of leaking car was determined. Slick Response was called out and found that the sample line plug was not installed and the valve was left in the open position. Slick Response closed the sample line valve and installed the plug to stop the leak. TCEQ was notified, report #20180178, due to the amount of product released. The leak was stopped at 1540 hours. Slick Response flushed the product on the ballast and in the immediate are with salt water and removed the residue liquid with a vacuum truck. The final flush of product from the contaminated area was performed on 1/22, a final report will be submitted to TCEQ.

column168: Upon arrival to Grassy Mountain Landfill, facility personnel noticed UN Specification Cargo Tanker with a reacting load. Facility personnel, in appropriate personal protective equipment, successfully neutralized the contents of the UN Specification Cargo Tanker, gathered samples and were able to offload into the landfill’s stabilization cell without further incident. Appropriate notifications made to internal Operations, Health & Safety and Transportation Compliance. Utah Department of Environmental Quality was notified of the reaction at 16:50 MST.
column169: Through rigorous investigation, the root cause of the reaction was determined to be a compromised internal liner exposing the concentration of the waste stream to the carbon steel tanker shell. Generator was informed at the time of the reaction, and communicated with throughout the investigation. It was agreed by the generator and the facility that the means of transporting the waste stream would be shifted to totes for the future. Additionally, the operational branch was retrained on UN Specification Cargo Tanker requirements and subsequent chemical resistant liner threshold requirements.

column168: During the morning hours of 01/03/2018, a LOPC PSE 1 event occurred while loading product phenol into a railcar. This railcar had previously been partially loaded and was to be filled the rest of the way with product for shipment to customer.  While loading the maximum capacity of the car was exceeded and approximately 3,717 gallons of 99.9% phenol went into secondary containment. This material subsequently breached the secondary containment and material entered the street and W-Sewer (PWD) before the leak was identified and isolated, release lasted approx 8 minutes. Plant emergency response team mitigated further entrance of material into the sewers. Notifications to outside agencies were made by plant personnel.
column169: Corrective Actions:  Re-train shipping department operators on loading procedures: specifically on FLS sign off and physical weigh ticket verification. Train Bridge Street guards that practice of providing heel volumes over the phone is unacceptable. Re-write SOPs for shipping department to remove ambiguity and other errors in the procedures. Improve lighting in the loading areas. Provide large flashlights for use in examining car interiors to shippers in their shanty areas. Determine if yard master system can provide heel volumes and help to mistake-proof the transfer of information. Perform an engineering evaluation of the secondary containment area for phenol/AMS railcar loading. Evaluate if we can place solid covers over sewer drains that are adjacent to loading areas. Capital project to implement an engineered overfill protection system on the railcar loading area.

column168: On January 18, 2018 the UTLX 203298 loaded with UN1993 Flammable Liquids, N.O.S. (Nonene) STCC 4912259 was found leaking in the BNSF railyard in Denver, CO. The leak was discovered by BNSF transportation personnel.  Upon further inspection the leak was found to have originated from the sample line under the combination housing.  The cause of the leak was a partially opened sample line valve and the secondary closure plug was not installed.  BNSF hazmat responder closed the sample line valve approximately one full turn which stopped the active leak.  He then properly installed the secondary closure plug.  This release resulted in several yard tracks shut down for a few hours to control ignition sources and allow for environmental remediation of the soil.  It is estimated that the liquid lost was 50 gallons, 25 of which was collected in a portable catch basin.  Response contractor handled remediation.  Two yard employees were taken to local hospitals for exposure evaluation.  Employee status not know at this time.
column169: Pre-trip inspection quality assurance audits to ensure compliance with applicable laws.  Investigation and accountability should ensue to intervene immediately on the cause of this securement failure.  Follow up auditing and re-training of all employees involved with loading and shipping of tank cars.

column168: While unloading a box van trailer for the purposes of consolidation, facility personnel noticed 3 drums were seeping from the drum ring closures, leading to total release of 1 g which impacted only the trailer floor; no soil or water was affected. An emergency crew wearing the correct personal protective equipment was summoned; they over-packed the three drums into suitable UN spec over pack drums of the correct UN specification. The trailer floor was cleaned, and the waste generated in the cleanup was placed inside the overpack drums. The waste continued to it's final destination without incident.     A management team investigation determined that these drums had not been adequately prepared for transportation, in that the drum ring gasket condition and gasket seating was questionable, and the drums likely lacked sufficient head space which led to build up of excess pressure.     This release fell below the state reporting guidelines.
column169: At the time these drums were placed into transportation, there was no evidence of a release. The generator has been contacted, and made aware of the issues at hand. We have asked the generator to retrain it's personnel on correct drum closure instructions, with an emphasis on being sure the drum ring gasket is in proper condition and that the drum ring is seated correctly using a dead blow hammer when required. We have also asked the generator to leave sufficient head space in drums.

column4: A specification cargo tank 1,000 gallons or greater containing any hazardous materials that (1) received structural damage to the lading retention system or damage that requires repair to a system int
column168: The cargo tank trailer was involved in a crash on an ice covered roadway. The truck struck a small pickup truck in the rear and left the highway to the right striking trees and a dirt embankment. The trailer rolled to the left landing on the driver side parallel to the roadway.     Emergency responders reported a possible drip from a pressure relief device located on the top of the cargo tank trailer. A containment device was placed under the valve. Later it was determined the valve did not leak. The material was water.     Miller personnel along with an ER contractor responded to the incident. The product was transferred from the rolled trailer into another cargo tank trailer. The rolled trailer was setup and removed from the highway. There was no release of product during this procedure. Product was returned to the shipper.    Several days later the ER contractor returned to smooth out the ruts in the state right of way and to seed the area with grass seed.

column168: CTCX 731519 was observed leaking from bottom outlet valve handle stem in track 23 at the PTRA North Yard at approximately 1100 hours on Tuesday, January 23. Intercontinental Terminals was notified along withe Slick Response. They arrived on scene and determined that product was leaking around the packing on the stem for the bottom outlet handle.  ITC personnel tightened the packing nut and were able to stop the leak. The car was observed for 24 hours with no further issues. Approximately two gallons of product were lost. The car is released for movement under and OTMA to return to ITC where it will be emptied and the valve handle inspected and repaired as necessary.
column169: ITC personnel responded and are investigating the incident. The car will be returned to their facility for off loading and further inspection of the packing and o-rings on the valve handle.

column168: During a routine inspection, facility personnel noticed a fiberboard package had become stained with what appeared to be oil. There was no release to the pallet or facility floor, only oil staining on the box. A response crew wearing the correct personal protective equipment opened the box to determine the cause. They did not discover any of the liquid filled capacitors to be leaking, and the box lining was intact. These capacitors, along with the oil-stained box, were repacked into an appropriate UN specification cubic yard box and continued to the final waste destination without further incident.     An investigation revealed that the original box had become stained during initial loading when a facility technician forgot to put a plastic liner into the box as required and then broke a capacitor while loading it into the box.  The oil from that break stained the fiberboard box, and the technician decides to reuse the same stained box after cleaning that release, putting a liner into the box as originally required.     This release fell below the state reporting guidelines.
column169: Both the driver who accepted this stained box into transportation and the technician who reused an oil-stained box were given retraining on proper hazardous materials package inspection and preparation, with an emphasis on making sure there is no residue or staining on the exterior of packages.

column168: WE IDENTIFIED THE ABOVE DESCRIBED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (LIMITED QUANTITY) AS AN ADDITIONAL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ON THE TRAILER. AS INDICATED BY THE PREVIOUS SUBMISSION, OUR DRIVER WAS DRIVING WEST ON I-20 NEAR NM 126, WHEN HE RAN OVER A MATTRESS IN THE ROADWAY. THERE WERE VEHICLE NEARBY AND THE DRIVER COULD NOT SAFELY MAKE EVASIVE MANEUVERS. THE MATTRESS EQUIPMENT IN HIS MIRROR, HE PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD. UPON INSPECTION, HE NOTICED THE MATTRESS ON FIRE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY WOKE THE CO-DRIVER FROM HIS SLEEPER BERTH. THE FIRE WAS TOO INVOLVED AT THE TIME TO USE A FIRE EXTINGUISHER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED 911 AND CALLED OUR OFFICE. ACCORDING TO THE CLEAN UP CREW, THE FREEWAY WAS BLOCKED FOR ABOUT TWO HOURS. THE TRACTOR, TRAILER AND PRODUCT ARE A TOTAL LOSS.
column169: OUR DRIVERS ARE INSTRUCTED TO ENSURE THEY ARE USING APPROPRIATE DEFENSIVE DRIVING TECHNIQUES. WE INSTRUCT DRIVERS TO USE APPROPRIATE EVASIVE MANEUVERS WHEN SAFELY POSSIBLE TO AVOID ROAD DEBRIS.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: ON 1-12-2018 AT APPROXIMATELY 0215 HRS, THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED ON A TRAILER FLOOR DURING A LOADING OPERATION WHERE THE LOADER IDENTIFIED WHAT HE THOUGHT WERE VISIBLE LIGHT COLORED FUMES EMINATING FROM THE PACKAGE. THE LOADER COMMUNICATED TO THE PICKOFF PERSON WHO NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR WHO WAS WITHIN 10 FEET WHEN THIS HAPPENED. I IMMEDIATELY ORDERED ALL PERSONNEL TO THE WEST END OF THE BUILDING WHILE I FURTHER INSPECTED THE PACKAGE. THE CLOUD DID NOT APPEAR TO BE IN A GAS STATE AS IT SETTLED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR. PPE WAS DONNED AND THE PACKAGE WAS CONTAINED IN A SPILL CONTAINER AND BROUGHT TO THE DMP AREA FOR INSPECTION. INSPECTION REVEALED THREE FIRE EXTINGUISERS OF WHICH ONE WAS SUBJECT TO A MINIMAL ACCIDENTAL DISCHARGE DUE TO A MISSING PULL PIN. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF THE PIN OR ITS SECURING MECHANISM THAT REMAINED IN THE BOX. BASED ON AN INTERVIEW WITH MYSELF, HAZMAT HELP DESK OPERATOR "CANDICE" ADVISED THIS TO BE AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT WITH REFERENCE # 554390.
column169: I RECOMMEND THAT THE MANUFACTURER INCLUDE ALL WORKING PARTS OF THE FIRE EXTINGUISHER. THERE WAS NOT PULL PIN PRESENT TO PRREVENT THE RELEASE OF THE DRY CHEMICAL. THIS PACKAGE WAS BEING SHIPPED TO A RETURNS DEPARTMENT.

column168: Driver accepted a lecture cylinder of 100% Chlorine. The cylinder had residue around the valve assembly but did not appear to be leaking. When the driver arrived back at the terminal, a strong chlorine odor was present in the cargo box of his vehicle. The driver immediately notified the branch management who secured the area and initiated a local emergency response. The internal emergency response personnel, after donning appropriate PPE assessed the situation and retrieved the cylinder and over packed same into a container rated for the material. The new package was shipped to its final destination without further incident.

column168: On January 20, 2018, at 1626 ET, Landstar Ranger notified ERTS that tractor #563256 / trailer #648932 was flagged down by someone who noticed the trailer leaking. Driver was located on I-35 Northbound in Mariette, OK (near mile marker 13) and was leaking approximately 10 Gallons of UN2810 to the asphalt of the interstate. No drains, waterways, or soils were impacted.     ERTS dispatched ERS of OK who arrived on site and determined that the tote had been damaged due to a crack at the bottom of the tote approximately 1 inch in length. ERS of OK transferred the tote into a new clean tote and placed granular absorbents on the impacted area of the asphalt. All waste was transported off-site and managed by ERS. Unknown what specifically caused the damage to the tote.

At 0858 ERTS was notified by Dohrn Transfer of a 40gal release of UN1903 Disinfectant, liquid, corrosive, n.o.s., 8 from a 275gal tote. The tote was punctured by a forklift while unloading. The terminal has placed oil dry in the trailer. ERTS has contacted Tradebe in response to the release. ERTS contracted with Tradebe for the response. The tote was transferred to a new tote, All waste was containerized and taking off-site for disposal.

On 1/23/18 at approximately 1430 hours a Schneider Transport truck was leaving the IMTT main gate when an IMTT employee observed product leaking from the trailer.  The truck pulled off to the side of the main building.  When responding personnel arrived they noticed a puddle of product accumulating near the trailer and confirmed it was a BASF gas additive AP-205-20M.  Responding personnel determined that the front wash out cap was missing and that the driver had failed to properly secure it.  Bayonne Police and Fire were notified as well as US Ecology (IMTT's OSRO) who performed a cleanup operation.  An IMTT Chemical Operator found the missing cap in the roadway and brought it to the scene to return it to the driver.  The driver re-secured the cap and the left the area after the cleanup operation was complete and responding agencies were satisfied.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident. The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company  and will address any incurred costs for the cleanup and/or loss of product.

column168: On 01/30/2018 at 0658 hours CSX train was reported derailed in Quincy, FL.  At around 0730 hours it was confirmed a release from covered hopper car KLRX525100, loaded adipic acid.  A small amount released from the top hatche as a result of the derailment when it went onto its side. The area was isolated and the shipper Derek Cargile ((316) 250-4925) was notified.  Hull’s Environmental, Hepaco, and Arcadis, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and discovered that approximately 100 pounds of product had been released from the top hatches as a result of the derailment and the car going onto its side. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper contact Derek Cargile ((316) 250-4925).         Tarrant, AL – 01/30/18 – KLRX525100– Adipic Acid

column168: An SK driver was placing 2/55g drums in the back of his box truck that were staged on his lift gate.  After placing the first drum in the truck, he started to move the 2nd drum when he notice material leaking from the bottom of the 1st drum.  The driver immediately started to contain the spill using absorbent material and then turned the drum upside down.  Clean Harbors F/S responded and completed the cleanup. The 55g drum was placed in an overpack and the overpack and clean up  material were sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility. It was determined the base of the drum was completely deteriorated and the drum should of been overpacked before the customer offered the drum for transportation.
column169: Safety-Kleen reached out to the customer and advise the customer that any containers being offered for transportation need to be inspected for any integrity issues.

column168: While transferring a drum from a truck to a temporary storage facility for the purposes of consolidation, facility personnel notice a drum had a small leak from the drum ring. The small release only impacted the van trailers floor; no soil or water were impacted. A response crew wearing the correct personal protective equipment was summoned; they over packed the drum into a suitable UN rated salvage overpack drum and placed all materials from the cleanup into the overpack as well. The drum continued to its final destination without incident. An investigation revealed that this drum had not been closed to the manufacturers' specification.     This release was reported to the CT DEEP #2018-00240, Dispatch #205.
column169: Both the facility personnel who loaded this drum, and the driver who transported the drum were given retraining on drum closure and inspection, with an emphasis on verifying all packages are closed to the manufacturers' specification using the appropriate torque wrenches and attachments, and on verifying package closure before shipment.

column168: The vent valve that drains the phenol loading arm was inadvertently left open after venting prior railcar.  Started loading the second railcar and noticed the valve was leaking phenol out. The leak occurred for approximately 2 minutes and estimated release to the containment area was 27 pounds.
column169: Insure valve is closed and make sure there's nothing obstructing the valve to be closed fully.

A response crew, wearing the correct personal protective equipment, was called in to over pack the drum and the cleanup waste materials into a suitable UN rated salvage over pack drum. This drum continued on to its intended destination without further incident.    The CT DEEP was notified #2018-00247.
column169: The driver who handled this drum was given retraining on the safest methods to move drums, specifically to use a proper drum cart where practical to avoid rolling a loaded drum on its edge on surfaces with obstructions or protrusions.

column168: Original comments:   QA was called to the Mezz for a leaking package. Upon inspection it was discovered that the package was a unprocessed undeclared flammable liquid hazmat, UN1263PAINT. The package had not DOT diamond labels or hazmat markings or indicatorsofany kind on the outer packaging. It was not until the metal pail inside the fiberboard box was discovered that it was identified as a flammable liquid hazmatthat had spilled. Absorb fold was laid down to soak up spillage, Leaking package and clean-up material was placed into a hazmat tote/bag and taken to the hazmat cage to be processed.    New Comments:

Original comments:   Package was taken out of system flow at an unknown time on Morning of 1/15/18 to small visible leak around the cap cover and lid. Inspection showed stains and droplets of brown liquid around the lid as well as on the Op-900 LL forms and packet that were affixed to lid. The cap cover was in place and not noticeable loose, but the pattern of the leak indicated it was the source of the spill. column168: Original comments:  MeeRan called for a QA about a damaged hazmat at 23:30. I answered the call andresponded right away. When I showed up to the Unload area, MeeRan had the hazmat in her hands and handed it to me. I then took the hazmat to the damage cage and put it in a red hazmat tote. I then went back to the spill site and started the clean up. I found a couple packages that were near the hazmat and removed them because they were wet. I then lifted one of the flaps and noticed that it spilled down into the belly of the trailer, so I called over the other QA (Kurt). After clean up, I talked to the PH about how he found the package and all of that. I then went and inspected the package. Upon inspection, I found a small puncture on one of the bottom corners. The puncture was smaller than a dime. There is no actual way to tell how the package was punctured, but with how small the hole is, it had to have been leaking for the whole time it was in the trailer. It is a possibility that it was punctured before or while it was being loaded at the origin station.   New Comments:

column168: While transporting a virgin diesel fuel load, the driver noticed he had a release of fuel streaming down his tanker trailer, and hitting the road. The driver immediately stopped and called for an emergency response. When parked and not moving, the vehicle stopped leaking, as the release was from the tank dome lid. The spill impacted asphalt, soil, and the nearby body of water. An emergency response crew wearing the correct personal protective equipment was summoned and fully cleaned and remediated the release. The South Portland Fire Department responded as well but did not assist in the actual cleanup. The South Portland Police Department provided traffic control. All waste generated from the cleanup was placed into the appropriate UN specification packages and disposed of in the appropriate waste stream.      An investigation revealed that the driver did not ensure the dome hatch was adequately closed before transportation; the movement of the truck while driving caused the fuel to splash from the unsecured dome lid. After the dome lid was fully tightened, the fuel load was delivered to it's intended destination without further incident.    The incident was reported to the State of Maine report #P-42-2018, US Coast Guard/NRC report #1202343.
column169: The driver of this tanker received formal disciplinary action for failing to adequately perform a pre-trip inspection of this tanker. In addition, the driver received retraining on completing thorough pre and post trip inspections, and a company required load verification checklist form ( a newly developed tool to help prevent this type of incident.)

column168: While loading a trailer for transport using a forklift and pallet, the material handler punctured a container. In appropriate personal protective equipment, the facility personnel attempted to move the compromised IBC, to properly transfer the contents to another UN Specification rated container, however some of the contents were released. Facility personnel were successful in remediating the area; the release was in containment, no water ways, soil or storm drains were impacted. Appropriate internal notifications were made and the waste was sent to it final destination without further incident. The release was below state reporting requirements, thus no state notification was made.
column169: Material handler was re-trained on forklift operations and a safety stand down meeting with the facility personnel was documented.   Key learning points from the incident were distributed in regional incident review meetings.

On 1/19/2018 a Landstar Ranger tractor-trailer was involved in a rollover accident on I-35 South bound at mile marker 69 near Cotulla, TX. 10 55-gallons steel drums of UN3082 Asterpode OPT 3 and 1 55-gallon steel drum of UN3082 Melon Mechacaps were crushed during the accident. A total of approximately 6 gallons of the products were released inside the trailer and into the soil. An environmental contractor overpacked the damaged drums and completed cleanup operations.

column168: On 01/18/2018 at 0045 ET, the driver for Dupre Logistics tanker #22095 experienced a UN1203 Gasoline spill at a Kroger Gas station in Nashville TN. It is reported that approximately 75 gallons of UN1203 gasoline released from the valve due to a mechanical failure. The release impacted the concrete lot and nearby drain. A contractor responded to perform cleanup. The drain was pumped with a vac truck and the concrete cleaned with granular absorbents. All waste debris was containerized and taken with the contractor for disposal.

column198: EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND TRAINING SOLUTIONS, INCORPORATED

column168: SHPX 213217 was identified by Lee Hudon with FRA during inspection.  BNSF Responders attempted to locate a release due to product on exterior and in protective housing but could not identify initially as the liquid line valve was suspected.  UTLX mobile repair was brought in to pressure the car up and the release was identified from the bolted liquid line flange between the flange and the pressure plate.
column169: Tank cars should be tested prior to offering for transportation to ensure the package is not active releasing while in transport.

column168: Carrier driver left shipper and parked CTMV approximately two (2) miles from the shipper.  Driver detected product odors when he exited the CTMV.  Driver discovered that a pressure release cap was laying in the crash box.  The cap had been installed on the pressure relief valve and was secure when the driver left the shipper.  The product was released from the open valve into the crash box and then released onto the pavement from the overflow tube.  The driver reinstalled the cap and the release stopped.  The duration of the release occurred no longer than 15 minutes.  An investigation is underway to determine the exact make/model/type of the valve and cap in question.  This information will be included in a supplemental report if needed.        Event #67737.

column43: DOWANOL PM GLYCOL EITHER STD BULK
column168: DRIVER CONDUCTED PRE-TRIP INSPECTION IN LANGER YARD ON TL#3298, SEALED ALL OUTLETS ON THE TRAILER AND PROCEEDED TO LOADING FACILITY AT OILTANKING IN CHANNAHON, IL; A VAC-TEST WAS PERFORMED AT SCALED HOUSE PRIOR TO LOADING. AFTER APPROVED TRAILER WAS SENT TO RACK TO RACK 7 FOR LOADING. ONCE LOADING WAS COMPLETED TRAILER 3298 STARTED TO LEAK OUT THE REAR SUMP FLANGE GASKET THAT SITS BELOW THE INTERNAL VALVE. IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT UP 10 1200 GALLONS SPILLED OUT INTO THE LOADING AREA. THIS WAS ALL CAPTURED IN THE LOADING AREA AND NO INJURIES TOOK PLACE. THIS SPILL WAS A RESULT OF A CATASTROPHIC GASKET FAILURE AT THE SUMP FLANGE. THE TRAILER IS DUE FOR ITS 5 YEAR PRESSURE TEST 01/29/2018. ALONG WITH ALL THE OTHER TRAILER TESTING REQUIRED BY THE DOT. THE SUMP GASKET HAD CHIPPING ON THE INNER GASKET EDGE ALLOWING PRODUCTS TO ATTACK THE INTEGRITY OF THE FILLER MATERIAL. THE CHIPPING IS A RESULT OF A FOREIGN SOLID OBJECT AT ONE POINT MONTHS PRIOR. THE FILLER WAS SATURATED AND THE VOID WAS FILLED WITH A SOLID BUILD UP BETWEEN THE FILLER AND THE GASKET INNER EDGE. AT THE POINT WHERE THE VALVE WAS HEATED FOR THE LOAD PRIOR THE GASKET SHOWS DEFORMATION AS A RESULT OF HEAT AND PRESSURE. THE FLANGE BOLTS WERE TIGHT BUT NOT TO THE FULLY RECOMMENDED TORQUE RATIO. A RESULT OF THE SATURATED FILLER MATERIAL. THIS LEAK/SPILL OCCURRED IN THE LOADING AREA AT THE LOADING FACILITY. THE PRODUCT THAT WA RELEASED WAS CAPTURED IN THE PITS OF THE LOADING AREA AND CONTAINED IN THE DISCHARGE WATER CATCH TANKS FOR THE LOADING SITE. NO EXTERNAL ENVIRONMENTAL EXPOSURE TOOK PLACE. THE GASKET FAILED AS A RESULT OF BEING CHIPPED AND COMPROMISED, THEN HEATED WITH STEAM AS THE TRAILER WAS UNDER PRESSURE DURING THE PRIOR LOAD, LIKELY MELTING THE ACCUMULATION OF SOLID CHEMICAL BUILT UP WITHIN THE GASKET HELPING TO SEAL AND MAINTAIN POSITION. THUS CAUSING THE GASKET TO DEFORM AND PARTIALLY TEAR BUT NOT TOTALLY FAIL. THE LOADING OF DOWANOL PM MUST HAVE LEAKED THROUGH THE CHIP HOLES IN THE INNER LIP OF THE GASKET AND DEGRADED THE SOLID PRODUCT (B) HELPING TO HOLD THE SUMP FLANGE GASKET TOGETHER IN ITS PARTIALLY FAILED STATE. WITH THE PRESSURE OF THE LOAD AND THE SOLVENT NATURE OF THE PRODUCT WE HAD A TOTAL CATASTROPHIC GASKET FAILURE.
column169: AS A RESULT OF AGE AND HEAT CYCLES TEFLON BECOMES BRITTLE, FOREIGN MATERIALS HAVE A TENDENCY TO DAMAGE THE GASKETS MORE EASY. THREE YEARS AGO LANGER IMPLEMENTED A COMPLETE GASKET CHANGE OUT PERIOD CORRESPONDING TO THE DOT PRESSURE TEST. THIS TRAILER IS DUE FOR IT’S DOT PRESSURE TEST, IT WILL BE THE FIRST CYCLED GASKET CHANGE ACCORDING TO THIS ADOPTED PROGRAM. THIS ACTION ELIMINATES THE TYPICAL SHIPPING FOUND IN TEFLON GASKETS.  IN ADDITION TO BRIDGE THE GAP FOR THE REMAINING REST OF THE FLEET, WHEN HEAT IS APPLIED TO THE SUMP OR ANY OTHE FLANGE GASKET WE WILL REMOVE THE TRAILER FROM SERVICE, INSPECT AND TEST THE FLANGE GASKETS.

column169: IN ORDER TO PREVENT RECURRENCE THE DRIVER WENT THROUGH REFRESHER TRAINING. A TRAINING REFRESHER PROGRAM AND OPEN DISCUSSION HUDDLES ARE GREAT TOOLS TO DECREASE THE FREQUENCY OF RECURRENCE.

column168: DURING A ROUTINE FACILITY INSPECTION OF A TEMPORARY STORAGE FACILITY, PERSONNEL NOTICED A DRUM LEAKING FROM WHAT APPEARED TO BE A PINHOLE PUNCTURE IN THE LOWER BOTTOM BODY OF THE PLASTIC DRUM. A RESPONSE CREW WEARING THE CORRECT PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT RESPONDED, OVER-PACKING THE DRUM AND ALL MATERIALS USED TO CLEAN THE AREA INTO A SUITABLE UN SPECIFICATION SALVAGE OVER-PACK DRUM. ONLY CONCRETE CONTAINMENT WAS IMPACTED; NO SOIL OR WATER SOURCES WERE AFFECTED. THE DRUM CONTINUED TO ITS INTENDED FINAL DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.    NO IMMEDIATE CAUSE OF THE PINHOLE PICTURE COULD BE DETERMINED; IT IS SUSPECTED TO HAVE HAPPENED DURING HANDLING.    THIS RELEASE FELL BELOW THE REPORTING REQUIREMENTS FOR THE STATE OF OHIO.
column169: AT THE TIME THIS DRUM WAS ACCEPTED INTO TRANSPORTATION, THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF A RELEASE. ALTHOUGH NO CONCLUSIVE ROOT CAUSE WAS ESTABLISHED, THE OPERATORS AT THE RECEIVING TRUCK TO TRUCK TEMPORARY STORAGE FACILITY WERE ASKED TO TAKE GREATER CARE WHEN HANDLING SPECIFICALLY PLASTIC WASTE FILLED DRUMS, BEING SURE TO AVOID UNNECESSARY CONTACT BETWEEN THE DRUMS AND OTHER DRUMS AND PALLETS.

column168: THE ADVANTAGE TANK LINES, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER GASOLINE INTO THE CUSTOMER’S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, IT APPEARS THAT THE STORAGE TANK OVER-PRESSURED DUE TO THE DRIVER NOT PROPERLY VENTING THE TANK. THIS CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 100-150 GALLONS OF GASOLINE TO BE RELEASED FROM THE STORAGE TANK. SUGAR RUN SPILLS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: ADVANTAGE TANK LINES, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE DELIVERY POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER DIESEL FUEL INTO THE CUSTOMER’S STORAGE TANK. IN THE COURSE OF DOING SO, THE CONNECTION BETWEEN THE HOSE AND THE TANK TRAILER BECAME COMPROMISED AND APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WAS RELEASED. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE RETAINING EARS ON THE DISCHARGE VALVE WERE WORN OUT AND WAS THE PROXIMATE CAUSE OF THE SPILL. SWS ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND HANDLED THE REMEDIATION. NO FURTHER ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS ANTICIPATED.
column169: KENAN TRANSPORT,LLC WILL MAKE THE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE RETAINING EARS ON THE DISCHARGE VALVE.

column168: While loading a waste stream from a customer facility tank into a tanker, a hose used for the transfer developed a pinhole release. The driver immediately shut down the transfer, cleared the hose of material, and called for assistance. The release impacted asphalt and snow on that asphalt; no soil or water sources were affected. An emergency response crew wearing the correct personal protective equipment cleaned the asphalt, the hose, and the impacted snow. The waste materials from the cleanup and the impacted snow were placed in drums of the appropriate UN specification and disposed of in the correct waste stream.     The driver replaced the defective hose with a good hose and completed the waste transfer without further incident.     An investigation found the hose to have had a small cut/abrasion which developed a pinhole leak.
column169: The driver was given retraining on hose inspection, with an emphasis on checking the exterior condition of hoses for cuts, tears, abrasions, or crimped areas.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ON JANUARY 4, 2018, AT APPROXIMATELY 23:45, A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 689 GALLONS OF NO. 2 FUEL OIL OCCURRED DURING ROUTINE FILLING OF A TANKER TRUCK DUE TO OPERATOR ERROR (DUST CAP ON DISCHARGE LINE WAS NOT PROPERLY SEALED). THE RELEASE IMPACTED ADJACENT PAVED SURFACES IN THE FUELING BAY AND THREE NEARBY CATCH BASINS. EMERGENCY RESPONSE ACTIONS, INCLUDING THE DEPLOYMENT OF ABSORBENTS, LIMITED THE FLOW OF THE OIL.   THE CATCH BASINS CONNECT TO AN OIL/WATER SEPARATOR SYSTEM. WHEN THE RELEASE OCCURRED, THE PUMPS IN THE OIL/WATER SEPARATOR SYSTEM WERE SHUT OFF TO PREVENT PUMPING OF THE RELEASED OIL THROUGH THE SYSTEM. INSPECTION OF THE OIL/WATER SEPARATOR SYSTEM CONFIRMED THAT THE OIL WAS CONTAINED IN THE CATCH BASIN STRUCTURES. ADDITIONAL RESPONSE ACTIVITIES INCLUDED THE DEPLOYMENT OF ABSORBENT BOOMS SURROUNDING THE CATCH BASINS, THE DEPLOYMENT AND COLLECTION OF GRANULAR ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND OIL ABSORBENT PADS, THE RELOCATED OF IMPACTED SNOW AND ICE TO CATCH BASIN DRAINAGE AREAS, AND THE RECOVERY OF APPROXIMATELY 7,000 GALLONS OF OIL-WATER MIXTURE FROM THE IMPACTED CATCH BASINS UTILIZING A VACUUM TRUCK. THE OIL-WATER MIXTURE WAS PUMPED INTO ON-SITE ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANK NO. 101. TWO DOT-APPROVED 55 GALLONS DRUMS OF SPENT ABSORBENT MATERIAL WERE GENERATED AND WILL BE DISPOSED OFF SITE.   ENVIRONMENTAL MEDIA, INCLUDING SOIL, GROUNDWATER, AND SURFACE WATER, WERE NOT IMPACTED BY THE RELEASE.
column169: DRIVER COMPLETED SAFETY TRAINING AT THE GULF TERMINAL PRIOR TO RETURNING TO THAT FACILITY. UPON THE DRIVER’S RETURN, A SECOND BURSAW DRIVER OBSERVED HIS LOADING PROCEDURE DURING TWO CONSECUTIVE EVENTS. BURSAW OIL & GAS (THE CARRIER AND RESPONSIBLE PARTY) CONDUCTED SPILL PREVENTION, CONTROL AND COUNTERMEASURE (SPCC) TRAINING ON FEBRUARY 14, 2018.

column168: Original comments:   Package was staged on dock during van unload/trailer load process. I (Ops Manage) noticed the package was wet from internal leaking and had the pkg inspected. Upon opening, discovered several internal packages. two of which were labeled "ORM-D" with orientation arrows, despite not being labeled as such on the outer most box. outer box does not contain orientation arrows or ORM-D indication. Liquid was found to be corrosive water boiler chemical treatment. One jug has a crack on the shoulder where the leak occurred. roughly 3/4 inch in length. Appears to beastress fracture from upside-down handling (recalling that there are no orientation arrows on outer box). No apparent dmg to outer or inner boxes. release may have begun on delivery van, but difficult to determine. Perhaps 3 hours release time,depending on when the package was damaged and not upright. Small amount of liquid released, most of which was absorbed by outer and inner boxes. Small drips on dock were neutralized and cleaned up using proper PPE and neutralizing powder. To mitigate the release, package was transported within station upright and in a hazmat tote.    New Comments:

Original comments:  Package loaded on HD van.  Refused at point of delivery.  Scanned damaged (wet)by driver.  Found on VSA next day - wet.   Package inspected by QA.  All four bottles showed signs of leakage due to loose caps.  Minimal amount leaked.. enoughto wet outer packaging.  Package processed as a damage.  New Comments:

column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THOUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: ASOX 291511 WAS NOTED AS LEAKING BY LOCAL MECHANICAL WORKERS. AN ODOR WAS ORIGINALLY NOTICED AND UPON CLOSER INVESTIGATION, A LEAK WAS NOTED FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR. THE CAR WAS SET OUT FOR INVESTIGATION. UPON ARRIVAL, BNSF HAZMAT MANAGER JEFF HANKINS INSPECTED THE CAR AND NOTED A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF LIQUID LEAKING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR. THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM UNDER THE COMBINATION HOUSING. AFTER OPENING THE HOUSING, ALL VALVES WERE IN THE CLOSED POSITION AND THE LEAK WAS OBSERVED AS EMITTING FROM AROUND THE PLUG ON THE LIQUID VALVE. THE PLUG WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED WITH A PIPE WRENCH. AFTER WAITING FOR APPROXIMATELY 5 MINUTES, LIQUID WAS ONCE AGAIN EMITTING FROM AROUND THE PLUG. THE PRESSURE (<10PSI) WAS RELEASED THE CAR TO ALLOW FOR REMOVAL OF THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG WAS ALSO LESS THAN TOOL TIGHTENED AND HAD NO SEALANT APPLIED.   UPON REMOVAL OF THE PLUG, LIQUID WAS NOTED BETWEEN THE VALVE AND PLUG. THE VALVE WAS CYCLED SEVERAL TIMES AND MINOR GROOVING IN THE BALL VALVE ITSELF WAS NOTED. THE PLUG WAS TAPED AND TOOL TIGHTENED IN THE LIQUID VALVE. THE VAPOR VALVE PLUG WAS TAPED AND TOOL TIGHTENED. UPON RE INSPECTION SEVERAL HOURS LATER, NO LEAKS WERE DETECTED. THE HOUSING WAS CLOSED AND SEALED.
column169: SHIPPER NEEDS TO ENSURE THAT THE PACKAGING IS PROPERLY INSPECTED AND PREPARED FOR TRANSPORTATION. THE LIQUID VALVE HAD A DEFECT AND BOTH PLUGS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND NOT PROPERLY SEALED WITH TEFLON TAPE OR PIPE DOPE.

column168: THE CFI PERSONNEL ON THE DOCK WERE UNLOADING THE TRAILER STAGING THE TOTES ON THE DOCK. WHEN THE PERSONNEL ENTERED THE TRAILER FOR THE LAST TOTE WHICH WAS POSITIONED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER IT WAS OBVIOUS THAT THE LAST REMAINING TOTE WAS LEAKING.   THE CFI PERSONNEL EXITED THE TRAILER AND CONTACTED THE DRIVER AND CFI CORP. THE SDS WAS REVIEWED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THE MATERIAL WAS A CORROSIVE LIQUID. THE CFI PERSONNEL HALTED ALL UNLOADING EFFORTS.   CFI CORPORATE CONTACTED EMI TO ASSIST WITH THE CLEANUP OF THE ESTIMATED ½ GALLON RELEASE OF PRODUCT.  EMI DISPATCHED A LOCAL CLEANUP CREW TO THE SITE, ONCE ONSITE THE CREW NOTICED THE LEAKING TOTE HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER AND PLACED ON THE DOCK. ONE OF THE DOCK PERSONNEL STATED THE LID ON THE TOTE WAS LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO SLOSH OUT DURING TRANSPORTATION.  THE CREW INSPECTED THE TOTE AND CONFIRMED THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE CAP. THE REMAINING OTHER 10 TOTE WERE INSPECTED TO ENSURE THE CAPS WERE SECURE.  THE CREW WIPED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE TOTE AND WIPED UP THE MINIMAL PRODUCT FROM THE TRAILER FLOOR AND RELEASED THE TOTE FOR DELIVERY.
column169: DURING THE LOAD PHASE EACH ITEM, TOTE DRUM OR CONTAINER OF LIQUIDS NEED TO BE INSPECTED TO ENSURE THE LIDS ARE SEALED TIGHTLY SHUT.

column168: ON 1/15/18, ADRIANA FUEL TRANSPORT DELIVERED #6 FUEL OIL TO THE MULTI-FAMILY RESIDENTIAL BUILDING AT 300 PELHAM ROAD, NEW ROCHELLE. THE PETROMETER ON THE BUILDING’S 5000-GALLON FUEL TANK INDICATED 3500 GALLONS WERE NEEDED. HOWEVER, DELIVERY WAS STOPPED AFTER UNLOADING 2245 GALLONS WHEN OIL WAS OBSERVED EXITING THE TANK VENT PIPE IN FRONT OF THE BUILDING. THE TANK DELIVERY DRIVER DID NOT IMMEDIATELY NOTICE THE OVERFILL. WHEN HE DID, HE DISCONTINUED PUMPING FROM THE TRUCK (THE TIME ELAPSED IS ON THE ORDER OF MINUTES). THE TANK DELIVERY DRIVER REPORTED TO THE NYSDEC HOTLINE THAT A SPILL OF 10 GALLONS WAS RELEASED.   ADJACENT TO THE VENT PIPE IS A STORM DRAIN, WHICH DRAINS DIRECTLY TO TITUS MILLPOND, A TRIBUTARY TO LONG ISLAND SOUND. (SEE FIGURE 1.) THE SPILLED OIL FLOWED INTO THIS DRAIN. IMMEDIATELY, THE BUILDING SUPERINTENDENT CLEANED UP ALL VISIBLE OIL AROUND THE DRAIN USING SORBENT MATERIAL. BECAUSE THE DRAIN AND GROUND WERE COVERED WITH ICE, IT WAS BELIEVED THAT ALL OIL HAD BEEN CAPTURED. DEC WAS SHOWN OUR EFFORTS AND INSPECTED THE SITE AND WAS CONTENT WITH THE EXTENT OF THE CLEANUP BY 1/16. WE BELIEVED THAT THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETE.   HOWEVER, ON 1/19.18, OIL WAS OBSERVED IN TITUS MILLPOND NEAR THE STORM SEWER OUTFALL AND ALONG THE SHORELINE. ON BEHALF OF THE BUILDING OWNER, I IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED NYSDEC AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC). THE BUILDING OWNER CONTACTED A CLEANUP CONTRACTOR, NORTHEAST ENVIRONMENTAL. NORTHEAST ARRIVED AT THE SITE THAT AFTERNOON AND INITIATED COMPREHENSIVE CLEANUP EFFORTS INCLUDING CONTAINMENT BOOMS, SWEEPS, AND SORBENT MATERIALS. MUCH OF THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED NEAR SHORE DUE TO EXTENSIVE ICE IN THE MILLPOND. DURING THE PERIOD 1/19/18 TO 2/7/18, NORTHEAST POWER WASHED THE ROCKS ON THE SHORELINE. THE BUILDING OWNER ALSO ARRANGED FOR THE STORM DRAIN PIPE TO BE STEAM WASHED. ALL NORTHEAST’S USED MATERIALS WERE DISPOSED OF AT TRADEBE RECYCLING IN BRIDGEPORT, CT. A MORE DETAILED CHRONOLOGY OF EVENTS IS PROVIDED IN APPENDIX A.  FOR THE SIX WEEKS FOLLOWING THE SPILL (AND CONTINUING TODAY), NORTHEAST PERFORMED MONITORING AND RE-POSITIONING OF THE BOOMS AND SWEEPS TO RESPOND TO STORMS, WIND, AND TIDAL FLUCTUATIONS. ALSO DURING THIS PERIOD, ANY VISIBLY OIL-COATED SURFACES WERE ADDRESSED USING SORBENT PADS. THE NYSDEC REPRESENTATIVE, TODD GHIOSAY, HAD CONTINUED TO MONITOR CLEANUP PROGRESS. WITH CONDITIONS BEING MUCH IMPROVED TODAY, THE OWNER ANTICIPATES RECEIVING PERMISSION FROM MR. GHIOSAY TO DISCONTINUE CLEANUP MEASURES IN THE NEXT TWO WEEKS.
column169: MEASURES TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE ARE AS FOLLOWS:  1. A NEW VENT WHISTLE WAS INSTALLED ON TANK.  2. OIL DELIVERIES HAVE BEEN DISCONTINUED THIS WINTER AND SINCE THE BUILDING HAS A DUEL FUEL BURNER AND USES GAS, AND THE WEATHER CONTINUES TO WARM, IT IS ANTICIPATED THAT NO FURTHER OIL DELIVERIES WILL BE NECESSARY UNTIL NEXT WINTER.   3. THE BUILDING IS SWITCHING TO #2 FUEL OIL IN ACCORDANCE WITH COUNTY REQUIREMENTS. WHEN THIS CHANGE OCCURS, A HIGH LEVEL ALARM AND NEW PETROMETER WILL BE INSTALLED ON THE TANK. IN ADDITION, THE VENT PIPE WILL BE LOCATED AWAY FROM THE STORM DRAIN.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTING FUEL FROM CHEVRON TO A GAS STATION WHEN A PASSING CAR ON INTERSTATE FLAGGED HIM DOWN SAYING HE WAS ON FIRE.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF OF INTERSTATE ONTO THE SHOULDER AND STOPPED. DRIVER OBSERVED DRIVE TIRES ON DRIVER SIDE OF TRUCK SMOKING AND HOT. DRIVER GRABBED FIRE EXTINGUISHER AND ATTEMPTED TO PUT HEAT SOURCE OUT BUT THE HEAT TURNED INTO FLAMES AND WAS NOT GOING OUT. DRIVER BACKED AWAY AND CALLED 911.  A SPECIALIST FROM THE INSURANCE COMPANY DETERMINED THAT IT STARTED WITH A MECHANICAL FAILURE AND WAS NOT DRIVER ERROR. UTAH DOT OBTAINED ALL MAINTENANCE RECORDS AND NO ISSUES. THE FINDINGS ARE UNCLEAR, POSSIBLY A DRAGGING BRAKE. THE ENTIRE TRANSPORT BURNED UP AND WAS DESTROYED.
column169: EMPLOYEES HAVE RECEIVED ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON CHECKING TIRES BRAKES WHEN DOING A PRE-TRIP AND WHILE STOPPED FOR ANY LENGTH OF TIME.   OUR COMPANY IS CURRENTLY IN CONTACT WITH TWO VENDORS REFERENCE PURCHASING EQUIPMENT THAT READS TIRE PRESSURE AND TEMPERATURE REMOTELY FROM THE CAB OF TRUCK.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS GOING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 7, AT THE TIME THE SPEED LIMIT WAS 35 MPH, GOING UPHILL, DRIVER WAS DOING 20 MPH. WHEN HE GOT TO THE TOP OF THE HILL, HE SAW THE SIGNS THAT SAID 7% STEEP GRADE NEXT 3 ½ MILES. HE PROCEEDED TO DROP GEARS AS HE WAS GOING DOWNHILL, THE TRUCK STARTED TO GAIN SPEED. DRIVER HIT THE BRAKE AND THE SURGE OF THE PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER WAS PUSHING THE TRUCK FORWARD. AS DRIVER TRIED TO FORCE THE TRUCK INTO 6TH GEAR, HE COULD NOT CONTROL HIS SPEED AND SOON LOST THE AIR BRAKES. HE PULLED TRAILER PARKING BRAKE AND TRUCK PARKING BRAKE. TRUCK WAS STILL RUNNING 25 MPH AS HE CAME TO A SHARP CURVE, SO DRIVER PULLED TO THE LEFT SIDE SHOULDER TO AVOID REAR ENDING A CAR. AS THE TRUCK HIT THE DITCH, IT AND THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER ONCE AND RAN INTO A TREE WHICH CAUSED THE BARREL OF THE TANKER TO BEND AND LET PRODUCT OUT OF THE MAN WAY WHICH CAME OPEN DURING THE ROLLOVER.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS INFORMED THAT HE NEEDED TO DRIVE ON CERTAIN HIGHWAYS AND NEVER TAKE ANY BACK ROADS. CONTINUE HIS PRE AND POST INSPECTIONS OF HIS EQUIPMENT.

column168: Driver was unloading REG at MUR8728. The vapor recovery on Murphy locations end  came off and about 15-20 gallons of regular spilled. This regular went into a storm drain that led to a retention pond. This was a Murphy equipment issue, not an ETC equipment issue. Murphy contacted their own environmental contractor, NRR, to clean up the site. This was the second time the Murphy vapor recovery popped of in as many deliveries. Before we delivered a second load after the first incident, ETC waited on an 'OK' from Murphy that their vapor recovery was fixed. Murphy sent ETC an email (1/24/18 5:26PM) stating that repairs were made and that ETC could deliver. Obviously, repairs on Murphy's end were not properly completed and ETC had a 2nd incident.    Due to Murphy equipment failure, Murphy handled all of the clean up and related expenses. We requested updates prior to completing this report but they would not provide an update.
column169: This was a Murphy equipment issue, not an ETC equipment or driver issue. Murphy contacted their own environmental contractor, NRR, to clean up the site.

column43: ULTRA LOW SULFUR ON ROAD DIESEL
column168: THE DRIVER USED A 3" CAMLOC AND ATTACHED IT TO THE ISO TANK FILL PORT. WHEN HE STARTED PUMPING THE CAMLOC FITTING CAME OFF OF THE ISO TANK FILL PORT. THE DRIVER DISENGAGED THE PUMP AND SHUT DOWN VALVE ON THE PUMP. DRIVER FOLLOWED PALMDALE OIL COMPANY’S REPORTING PROCEDURE. THE OSRO (CLIFF BERRY INC.)(CBI) WAS NOTIFIED AND SHOWED UP AT THE LOCATION WITH IN 20 MINUTES. THEY STARTED PUTTING DOWN OIL DRY TO KEEP ANY MORE PRODUCT FROM GETTING IN THE STORM DRAIN THAT LEADS TO THE WATERWAY. THE RELEASE WAS ABOUT 1 MINUTES TIME. CLIFF BERRY INC. STATED USING A VAC TRUCK TO SUCK FUEL OUT OF STORM DRAINS. THEY GOT DIAGRAM OF STORM DRAINS TO DETERMINE WHERE THE DRAINS WERE AND WHICH ONES WOULD BE AFFECTED. OIL ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE PLACED IN THE LAST INTERUM BOX TO KEEP ANYTHING FROM REACHING THE WATERWAYS. CBI PLACE OIL ABSORBENT BOOMS IN THE NEXT STORM DRAIN AFTER THE LAST AFFECTED STORM DRAIN. OIL DRY AND OIL ABSORBENT PADS WERE USED TO SOAK UP ALL OF THE MATERIAL ON THE ASPHALT PAVING. THAT WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL BY CBI. THE WATER AND FUEL MIXTURE WAS REMOVED FROM THE STORM DRAINS WITH THE VAC TRUCK. THE MATERIAL IN THE VAC TRUCK WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF BY CBI. I HAVE ATTACHED MANIFEST AND INVOICE FROM CBI. FLORIDA DEP WAS NOTIFIED AND A REPRESENTATIVE SHOWED UP TO THE SCENE. A DISCHARGE REPORT WAS FILED WITH THE STATE OF FLORIDA DEP (ATTACHED).
column169: IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER USED THE WRONG CAMLOC FITTING TO FILL THE ISO TANK. WE HAVE STARTED TO BE EXTRA CAUTIOUS WITH ISO TANK FILLING. WE HAVE STARTED TO DO MORE TRAINING ON HOW TO DO THIS. WE HAVE ALSO DEVELOPED AN ISO TANK FILLING PROCEDURE (ATTACHED).

column168: DRIVER WAS DISPATCHED WITH MORE FUEL THAN WOULD FIT IN THE AGST. HE STARTED THE DELIVERY AND STEPPED UP INTO THE CAB TO CHECK PAPERWORK. THE DELIVERY TANK OVERFILLED, SPILLING #2 DYED DIESEL FUEL ONTO THE GROUND. THE DRIVER DID NOT NOTICE THE OVERFILL FOR MOST OF A MINUTE. ONCE HE NOTICED, HE SHUT DOWN THE FLOW AND USED SORBENTS AND SNOW TO MINIMIZE THE SPREAD OF THE FUEL. HE REPORTED THE SPILL TO THE CUSTOMER AND OUR COMPANY. MORE SORBENTS WERE DISPATCHED TO THE SITE TO MINIMIZE MIGRATION. SANDBOX CONSTRUCTION WAS RETAINED TO REMEDIATE THE SITE. CONTAMINATED WASH WATER WAS REMOVED.
column169: THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED DELIVERING INTO A TANK THAT HAS NO GAUGE. THERE IS AN ELECTRONIC MONITOR, BUT THE DRIVER HAS NO ACCESS TO THE READINGS. BOTH THE MANAGER THAT ORDERED THE LOAD AND THE DRIVER SHOULD HAVE RECOGNIZED THAT THE LOAD WOULD NOT FIT INTO THE TANK. THE PRIMARY CAUSE WAS ORDERING TOO MUCH FUEL TO BE DELIVERED. THE DRIVER, HOWEVER, FAILED TO FOLLOW SEVERAL COMPANY POLICIES THAT WOULD HAVE PREVENTED OR MINIMIZED THE SPILL. HE FAILED TO VERIFY THAT THE LOAD WOULD FIT BEFORE UNLOADING. HE FAILED TO NOTIFY DISPATCH THAT THE DELIVERY TANK WAS DID NOT HAVE A GAUGE. HE LOAD WOULD FIT BEFORE UNLOADING. HE FAILED TO NOTIFY DISPATCH THAT THE DELIVERY TANK WAS DID NOT HAVE A GAUGE. HE FAILED TO REMAIN OUT OF THE CAB AND VIGILANT DURING DELIVERY.  WE ARE WORKING TO GET THE DRIVERS ACCESS TO THE MONITOR READINGS FOR TANKS WITHOUT A GAUGE. OTHER THAN THAT, THE CURRENT POLICY ALREADY SHOULD HAVE PREVENTED THE OVERFILL IF THE DRIVER HAD FOLLOWED IT. THE DRIVER RECEIVED A DISPENSARY SUSPENSION AND ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO EMPHASIZE THE POLICIES THE POLICIES THAT WERE NOT FOLLOWED.  ULTIMATELY, SIMILAR OVERFILLS ARE LIKELY TO CONTINUE SO LONG AS DELIVERIES CONTINUE ON TANKS WITHOUT A GAUGE. WE ARE EXPLORING THE OPTIONS FOR WORKING WITH CUSTOMERS TO HELP THEM GET PROPER GAUGES ON THEIR TANKS.

THE TRANSPORT SERVICE, LLC UNIT WAS TRAVELING ON WEST STREET IN VINTON, LOUISIANA. THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO MAKE A RIGHT TURN FROM A TIGHT AREA AND IN THE PROCESS THE REAR TIRES ON THE TRAILER WENT OFF THE ROADWAY INTO A DITCH. THIS CAUSED THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO ROLL OVER. THERE WAS NO RELEASE OF THE TOLUENE DIISOCYANATE THAT WAS LOADED ON THE TANK TRAILER. THE UNIT WAS SET UPRIGHT WITHOUT INCIDENT. A FEW LOCAL BUSINESS WERE EVACUATED DURING THE RECOVERY PROCESS.
column169: TRANSPORT SERVICE, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE DRIVING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column168: ON JAN. 1, 2018 APPROX. 04:45 AM CLIFFORD FUEL DRIVER COMPLETED LOADING OUR TANKER. LOADING RACK PUMP HAD SLOWED & STOPPED RUNNING. THEN THE OVERFILL ALARM BEGAN TO GO OFF AND FUEL STARTED TO FLOW ONTO RACK FLOOR. OUR DRIVER RAN TO SHUT DOWN THE MAIN GATE VALVE TO THE ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK. THIS STOPPED THE OVERFLOW OF HEATING FUEL. WE CALLED THE POSTED BUCKEYE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TO REPORT. TERMINAL STAFF ARRIVED AND PERFORMED CLEAN UP. SPILL WAS 100% CONTAINED IN SEPARATOR AT LOADING RACK. WE WERE TOLD TO LEAVE BY BUCKEYE MANAGEMENT. BUCKEYE HAD REPORTED SPILL AND WE HAD NOTHING TO DO WITH IT. BUCKEYE HAD AN EQUIPMENT FAILURE THAT DID NOT ALLOW VALVE TO CLOSE PROPERLY. AT TIME OF OCCURRENCE BUCKEYE ESTIMATED SPILL TO BE 190 GALLONS.
column169: AFTER A REVIEW BY BUCKEYE SAFETY MANAGEMENT; IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE “DANLOAD” EQUIPMENT MALFUNCTION WAS 100% FAULT OF INCIDENT, THAT APPROX. 80 GALLONS OF FUEL WAS SPILLED. ALSO: CLIFFORD FUEL DRIVER AND EQUIPMENT HAD OPERATED CORRECTLY AND HAD NO WAY TO FORESEE, AVOID, OR CORRECT WHAT HAD OCCURRED.  TERMINAL MANAGER ON CALL NIGHT OF OCCURRENCE WAS BILL KOLWAITE (315) 750-2754. HE HAS OFFERED HIS FULL ASSISTANCE IF YOU NEED ANY BETTER INFORMATION.

column168: Consignee handles unloading. Consignee representative found external outlet valve would leak after opening the internal valve. Leaking product was caught in bucket. Driver replaced the QRB gasket but this did not stop the leak. Driver was told he would not be unloaded. All valves were closed and observed to be leak free and driver was allowed to leave the plant and took the trailer to a Miller shop for evaluation and repair. The external valve was found to have a hair line fracture on the inside of the external flange at the weld. The external valve was replaced and bracing was installed on the discharge line to reduce the stress on the line at that location. Driver returned to the consignee and the product was unloaded into customer receiving tank without incident.

TILX 111522 was found releasing Acid in the UPRR Nampa yard. The shipper was notified of the release  and responded to make the repair. After inspection it was found that three of the liquid line flange bolts were less than tool tight. Repairs were made and the car continued to destination.

Norfolk Southern personnel found tank car DOWX73174 leaking around the bottom outlet valve. Upon inspection the leak was caused by a missing gasket between the bottom outlet flange and the tank car. Contents of the tank car were transferred into another tank car..

During FRA inspection inspector found the tank car to be leaking from the Manway cover. The manway cover was unsecured and the gasket was inspected to find a misaligned gasket. The gasket was re-aligned and the cover secured . The car was released back to transportation

column168: Univar USA picked up several Hazardous waste drums from our customer in Ashtabula, OH.   One of the drums leaked some of the liquid material from the bung on the top of the open head drum.   Material was present on the top lid of the drum.   We believe this leak happened while the driver was backing into the declined slope dock at Univar's Twinsburg Facility, as the drip marks down the drum were fresh.  The liquid level of the material was also filled up to the threaded portion of the bung closure, which probably played a significant role in this leak.

Original comments:   The pre loaders but the box aside for inspection because it was wet/bad smell. They saw it was on a lot of packages and set those aside as well. I went to inspect the wet packages for damage and all were good except the lantern/heater. There wasn't any indicator that there was a hazardous material on the packaging but was apparent it contained kerosene. The kerosene leaked out of the lantern somewhere near the base, and then out of the box either by soaking through or in the corners where it was not taped. Total duration was about 30-45 minutes.
